snippet: As Democrats pick through the wreckage of the campaign, one lesson is clear: The election was notable as much for the people who did not show up, as for those who did....
abstract: Some residents of Election District 15 in Milwaukee discuss their reasons for not voting in election; area, populated mostly by blacks and known for its high rates of poverty and incarceration, experienced 19.5 percent drop in voter turnout from 2012; many cite disillusionment with Pres Obama and presidential contenders as reasons for not voting; city's election commission says new state photo ID requirement may have also contributed to decline by preventing thousands from voting.

byline.contributor: Michael Wines contributed reporting from New York.

lead_paragraph: As Democrats pick through the wreckage of the campaign, one lesson is clear: The election was notable as much for the people who did not show up, as for those who did.

headline.main: Many in Milwaukee Neighborhood Didn’t Vote — and Don’t Regret It
headline.print_headline: ‘Both of Them Were Terrible’:  No Vote, No Regrets in Milwaukee
